title: For Sale:  Zastava 7.62x25 M57 .32 Tokarev Holster & 1 Magazine 762 32 late 1960s to early 1970s Cold Warrior Yugoslavian State Police
postcontent:
Our # HG7.62x25M57

Here is a Cold Warrior pistol from our opponents’ side, a genuine Zastava Yugoslavian manufactured model M57 steel frame Tokarev design pistol, chambered in the powerful 7.62x25 or .32 Tokarev caliber. This pistol came from service with the Yugoslavian State Police in what is now the State Union of Montenegro and Serbia, and comes with its brown leather police holster and cleaning rod. The Soviets pirated John M. Browning’s 1903 design and modified and chambered the new pistol for their purposes in the 1930s to replace their revolvers, then shared their milling equipment to entice the Independent Yugoslavs during the Cold War. This pistol is every bit as good as its Russian made counterparts. Several of thisM57’s ancestors saw action against the Nazi Army in World War II. Zastava Arms began production in their Kragujevac Serbia plant for Tito’s Communist Army in 1957, hence the model name, on Russian Milling Equipment. From this one’s J serial number prefix, it was manufactured in 1967, as the State Police addressed death and fallout from the Marburg virus. Its only alien marking is importation stamps located on the left forward section of its slide, and required by the 1968 Gun Control Act. These M57s have moderate surface detractions, mostly holster whitening on the slide edges and palm contact whitening or browning on the grip frame front and back straps. We rate them  as Good, perhaps Very Good, 70 percent vicinity by our estimate; photos, at any rate, ought to suffice for our distinguished shoppers to judge finish grade for themselves. Bore shows strong sharp rifling lands with some dark etchy texture in the grooves, and the chamber and mechanism are clean.As far as Specs, type is blowback single action semi-auto; caliber 7.62x25 Tokarev, and the magazine is outfitted for its original lanyard loop, and capacity is 8 + 1 rounds. Barrel length is 4 1/4 inches with full length steel guide rod; sights are blue steel dovetailed low blade front with u-notch high dovetailed steel rear; weight empty is 28.4 ounces with center of gravity at the trigger guard junction to the grip frame; grips are classic Soviet style serrated polymer. This pistol has a main safety for cocked-and-locked position, but does not have a magazine safety; that is, it will fire a single round even if the magazine is not in battery. Bore shows strong sharp rifling lands with some dark etchy texture in the grooves, and the chamber and mechanism are clean. We’re offering these attractive, collectable Zastava M57 pistols, each	for only	$ 169.00. 	Not transferable to civilian residents of California, the District of Colombia, or Massachusetts. I am selling my WASR AK. I am a former Marine Corps 2111/Small Arms Repair Technician, so be assured I have taken great care of this rifle over the years, and have added a few minor modifications. I took the wooden furniture off and re-finished it giving it a rich reddish-brown color, semi-gloss. I added a recoil buffer to keep the bolt and piston assembly from slapping into the receiver, dampening the recoil and wear on the rifle. I polished the bolt, giving it a smoother action, I also took a dremmel to the feed ramp ensuring a smoother more reliable feed. Along with the rifle I am including 8 magazines (7 steel surplus "ridgeback" mags, and 1 10rd Tapco mag) 30rds of Wolf 122gr HP ammunition, a Leapers red/green dot sight, a quick release scope mount, a Knight Armament vertical grip, and a BLACKHAWK! quick release sling. title: For Sale:  L1A1 FAL
postcontent:
This is an early 90's Imbel century import of a real and uncommon New Zealand Air Force L1A1. A 1962 manufactured Australian\New Zealand Inch Pattern rifle on a top quality Imbel metric receiver. The barrel is prior to 1961 as per the "L" date code. Bore is bright and shiny. Barrel and gas block are Lithgow made, Aussie. Bolt and carrier are Aussie. Bolt has spent some time in a British FAL that was serial number UBA 117976. Stock is NZ air force with the brass disc. Has an Aussie folding charging handle which would be correct for an NZ. Having marked laminate hand guards. Originally this 1962 rifle would have had solid wood hand guards so the laminates are replacements, but the wood often cracked or were broken so the replacements would also be correct. Flash hider is British made by BSA in 1960. Front sling swivel and bolt hold open are British. Takes inch or metric mags. According to Skennertons book (as per the serial numbers) this rifle is/was part of a contract run for New Zealand. Comes with 2-20rd mags and 1-30rd mag. One 20rd mag and the 30rd mag are DSA mags. Original sling included
